@S10 = The °·rama Scheme
The <193>·rama scheme of life, designed to sublimate the basic instincts ç
of a human being, may now be described briefly. According to this, ç
the life of an individual was divided into four <193>·ramas or stages ç
of life. They are: brahmacarya (student-hood), g<193>rhasthya (married ç
state), v<193>naprastha (the state of forest recluse) and sa<221>ny<193>sa ç
(monkhood).
Brahmacarya, the first stage of life, was usually of twelve years' ç
duration (from the seventh or eighth to the nineteenth or the twentieth ç
year). It was mainly devoted to study and discipline. The student ç
was required to stay in the gurukula or the house of his teacher and ç
learn the sciences†sacred as well as secular†and the arts.
These  teachers  in  ancient  India usually lived in hermitages not ç
far from the towns. The children under their care lived under the ç
same roof without any distinction of wealth and status, all leading ç
a hard, austere life. Serving the teacher and actively participating ç
in the household duties were as much part of their life as learning ç
the Vedas and mastering secular sciences. Begging the food, eschewing ç
the pleasures of life (in which brahmacarya or celibacy was the most ç
important) and abstaining from the affairs of the world were a prominent ç
part of their training.
After returning home, the student, now a young man, was expected to ç
marry and raise a family. Since marriage was considered as a sa<221>sk<193>ra ç
or a sacrament, and the wife as a life-mate in righteous living, it ç
was not considered as an obstacle to spiritual evolution. The g<216>hastha ç
or the householder was expected to earn well by righteous means and ç
live a happy and decent life which had to be socially useful. Among ç
his principal duties were the pa<210>cayaj<210>as or the five daily ç
sacrifices: devayaj<210>a (offering oblations to Indra and other deities ç
into the duly consecrated Vedic fires), <216><218>iyaj<210>a (appeasing ç
the <216><218>is or the sages by study and teaching of the Vedas), ç
pit<216>yaj<210>a (obsequial offerings to the departed manes), n<216>yaj<210>a ç
(feeding guests and hungry persons) and bh<220>ta- yaj<210>a (feeding ç
the domestic animals).
At the approach of old-age, the householder was to hand over the responsi-bilities ç
of the family to his children and retire to the forest along with ç
his wife if she was willing, or alone, if she was not. In this stage ç
known as v<193>naprastha (vana= forest; prasth<193>na = going) he ç
was to lead a contemplative life, in spiritual pursuits. It was actually ç
a life preparatory to the final stage, sa<221>ny<193>sa.
When this vanaprasthin or the forest recluse felt enough inner strength ç
to totally renounce all possessions and lead the life of an itinerant ç
monk, he could embrace sa<221>ny<193>sa or the monastic life, after ç
sending his wife to be taken care of, by the children. In this stage ç
of life, he had to move about constantly from place to place, begging ç
his food and spending his entire time in contemplation on God. He ç
was to practise self-control, freedom from desires and attachments, ç
and, universal love.
Though these four <193>·ramas were intended to be adopted successively, ç
excep- tions were allowed in special cases, so that one could take ç
sa<221>ny<193>sa even from the first or the second stage.
It appears that only the br<193>hma<207>as were considered competent ç
or eligible to adopt sa<221>ny<193>sa.
Some additional†but useful†information about the four <193>·ramas ç
may now be given here:
A brahmac<193>rin, living in the house of his guru, as a celibate, ç
could, if he so desired, continue specialization in Vedic studies ç
for 24 or even 48 years.
Eight types of marriage have been mentioned out of which only four ç
were considered as pure and legal. They are: br<193>hma (the gift ç
of a daughter by the father to a man learned in the Vedas and of good ç
conduct), daiva (the gift of daughter to the presiding priest of a ç
Vedic sacrifice), <193>r<218>a (giving away one's daughter after receiving ç
from the bridegroom [for the fulfilment of the sacred law] a cow and ç
a bull) and pr<193>j<193>patya (gifting of the daughter by the father, ç
stipulating the condition that the bridegroom remain monogamous and ç
be faithful to her).
Tying of the ma<209>galas<220>tra (or ma<209>galapratisara) (the thread ç
with an amulet, signifying auspiciousness to the bride) by the bridegroom ç
seems to be a later social custom, not mentioned in the dharma·<193>stras.
@S10 = Status of Women
Here, we can dilate a little, on the status and condition of women ç
in India. During the Vedic age they were given a high place in the ç
society. The mention of women sages like V<193>c, Ambh<216><207><200>, ç
Roma·<193> and G<193>rg<200> in the Vedic lore corroborates this view. ç
Women could undergo the upanayana sacrament and pursue Vedic studies. ç
Those who chose this path were called `brahmav<193>din<200>s.' The ç
others who did not pursue this path but chose to enter into the married ç
life straight-away, were called `sadyovadh<220>s.' Co-education seems ç
to have existed in the earlier period. K<218>attriya ladies got training ç
in the use of arms and other martial arts. Both kany<193>viv<193>ha ç
(marriage of a pre-puberty girl arranged by her parents) and prau<195>haviv<193>ha ç
(marriage after attaining puberty) were prevalent. Under certain circumstances, ç
the girl had the freedom to choose her husband.
The wife known as `g<216>hi<207><200>' was considered as `hal<%22>f<%0>' ç
of the husband and constituted the real `g<216>ha' or home. She was ç
called `s<193>mr<193>j<210><200>' (the queen or the mistress of the ç
home) and had an equal share in the performance of religious rites.
Divorce and remarriage of women were allowe<%26>d<%0>under very special ç
conditions.
Shaving of the hair and wearing red saries by the widows or their ç
committing sahagamana (dying on the funeral pyre of their dead husbands) ç
was never compulsory. The former custom seems to have been confined ç
to a small section of the br<193>hma<207>as, that too in South India. ç
The idea, perhaps, was that their life should be similar to that of ç
the sa<221>ny<193>sins.
It is interesting to note that ve·y<193>s (prostitutes) were allowed ç
to make a living, in the society, but were regulated by a code of ç
conduct specially made for them!
The devad<193>s<200>-system (devad<193>s<200> = a girl or a woman ç
`married' to the God in a temple and expected to spend her life as ç
his servant-maid) seems to be a later development.
@S10 = Some More Aspects of Social Life
Now, a few more aspects of Hindu social life, may be described:
Though <193>tmahaty<193> or suicide was severely condemned as a sinful ç
act, it was allowed as a ritual under very special conditions such ç
as old-age decrepitude, incurable diseases causing much suffering ç
to oneself and to others, as a pr<193>ya·citta or expiation for heinous ç
sins, for protecting one's religion and honour and so on. As far as ç
possible, such ritual suicides were to be committed in t<200>rthak<218>etras ç
(holy places, places of pilgrimage).
Formal conversions into Hinduism from alien religions do not seem ç
to have existed. Foreigners just adopted the Hindu way of life and ç
were absorbed into the society.
However, patitasa<221>sk<193>ra and ·uddhi (expiations and purification ç
for those fallen from the Hindu way of life) (patita = one who is ç
fallen) were very much prevalent and appropriate rites had been prescribed ç
for the same.
Many taboos existed with regard to food since it was believed that ç
food affected the mind also. Pure food was conducive to purity of ç
mind. Hence, rules and regulations were set out about food and eating†what ç
to eat and what not to eat; how to eat and how not to eat and so on.
M<193><221>sabhojana (eating of flesh) wascommon during the Vedic ç
period. However, it was later on discouraged† though tolerated†due ç
to the influence of Jainism and Buddhism.
Though sur<193>p<193>na (drinking of wine) existed, it was severely ç
condemned as a heinous sin.1
P<193>ka·<193>stra (the culinary art) was well-developed, Nala and ç
Bh<200>ma being the legendary experts in this field.
Dh<220>map<193>na (smoking of fragrant substances) and use of snuff ç
(special medicinal powders, only for curing certain diseases) have ç
been mentioned. Smoking and taking snuff, as we know them today, did ç
not exist.2
Cotton, woollen and silk cloths were in use since several centuries ç
before the Christian era. Unstitched clothes were preferred. Though ç
dhoti and c<193>dar (or chaddar or uttar<200>ya, upper wearing cloth) ç
were common, long shirts, pyjamas and coats were not unknown. Several ç
types of head-dresses, saris and bodices for women were in use.
Several attractive styles of dressing hair and wearing of ornaments ç
(by both men and women) existed, reflecting the zest for life.
Wrestling, polo, playing of cards had their origin in India and were ç
quite popular. There were many other games† simple but exciting and ç
exhilarating† inculcating and embellishing good sportsmanship.
From the foregoing portrayal of the Hindu society one thing stands ç
out as supreme: Life is not a curse but a great gift of God. It ç
must therefore be lived well. Though mok<218>a is the ultimate goal ç
of life, all aspects of life should be taken into consideration, ç
each being given its due place, but always in harmony with all the ç
other aspects.
It is this understanding and conviction of the Hindu religious and ç
social leaders that has imparted stability as well as resilience to ç
the society over the millennia.
