@S10 = Introduction
No society can survive for long, despite immense wealth and military ç
might, if it does not have a proper system of jurisprudence that can ç
give justice impartially to all its members. Impartiality is the life ç
of justice, and justice, of good government. There can never be any ç
justice without mature wisdom which alone knows how to strike a balance ç
between individual liberty and social good. This is exactly what the ç
sources of Hindu law have done, right from the Vedas upto the sm<216>tis ç
and dharma·<193>stras, as also the various nibandhas (digests).
However, the Artha·<193>stra of Kau<219>ilya (300 <MS>B.C.<D>) being ç
the oldest among the best organized works on secular codes of law, ç
can throw a lot of light on Hindu jurisprudence. It refers to more ç
than 12authors of the earlier period. It mayhence be safely relied ç
upon while discussing or presenting this subject.
