No civil action could be started without a complaint, which again, ç
could be lodged only by the aggrieved person. A regular petition to ç
the court was necessary. This was taken down by a `lekhaka' or a writer, ç
well-versed in the legal terms. He could put questions to the plaintiff ç
for clarifications if necessary. Then  summons  were  issued  to  the ç
concerned  person.  Obedience  to  the summons was enforced, by sanctions ç
or legal restraint, called `<193>sedha'.
This restraint could be of four kinds, as to: sth<193>na or place; ç
prav<193>sa or journey; time or period; and, certain actions. In other ç
words, till the dispute was settled, the defendant (or respondent) ç
should not go out of his house or place of residence, should not undertake ç
any journey, should present himself at the court on the day and at ç
the time fixed for it and should not do certain actions connected ç
with the dispute.
The plaintiff was required to repeat the charges in detail in the ç
presence of the defendant. This was taken down again by the lekhaka. ç
Any discrepancy between the earlier and later versions of the complaint ç
could lead to the dismissal of the case.
Pleading had to be precise, comprehensive,  unequivocal,  consistent  and ç
susceptible of proof.
Defence had to be confined only to the   points   raised,   answers   being ç
unhesitating, clear and consistent.
The defence could take any one of these four forms: 1) Confession; ç
2) Denial; 3) Special exception; 4) Plea of a former judgement.
The   judicial   proceedings   were generally in four stages: the ç
