The sages of India never considered religion and science as two conflicting ç
areas of knowledge. To them both were equally important, one being ç
the quest for the truth within and the other, without. They were actually ç
two facets of the same vidy<193> or science. Thatiswhy they were ç
called par<193>vidy<193> (higher knowledge) and apar<193>vidy<193> ç
(lower knowledge).
The word `<216><218>i'†generally translated as a `sage'†just signifies ç
a man of knowledge, in any field for that matter, since it is derived ç
from the root verb `<216><218>' (`to know'). Thus, if Vasi<218><219>ha ç
and Vy<193>sa were <216><218>is in the field of spiritual wisdom, ç
Dhanvantari, Var<193>hamihira and Bh<193>skara were <216><218>is in ç
the fields of medicine, astronomy and mathematics.
One thing which was basic to allthese <216><218>is was that their ç
j<210><193>na or knowledge was always meant to be used within the ç
