@S10 = Introduction
The desire for conquest is inherent in human beings. Conquest, however, ç
can be of two types: physical conquest through war and violence; cultural ç
conquest through the head and the heart. Histories of nations over ç
the centuries have proved that it is the latter that survives whereas ç
even the traces of the former may be thrown out when the conquered ç
nation rebels and reasserts itself, regaining its lost freedom.
The cultural conquest has another, a tremendous, advantage. The heart ç
can mellow the head when the latter displays arrogance. And, the head ç
can harden theformer if it leads to debilitating sentimentalism.
The way Hindu culture, based on the multifaceted Hindu religion, has ç
quietly spread far beyond the geographical boundaries of India, proves ç
this theory. It is the sages and savants, sans the Sword and sans ç
the Book, that went out of this country to other regions of the globe ç
to spread the message of universal love and brotherhood. They were ç
least interested in political colonization or accumulating wealth ç
through trade and commerce. India had plenty of military power and ç
wealth. In fact it is the latter that tempted the foreigners from ç
the Middle-East and the West to set off a series of savage invasions ç
against this country. That neither the Hindus nor their religion and ç
culture were wiped out of this land†on the other hand, they are still ç
going strong†is proof enough of the wonderful religio-cultural resilience ç
of the Hindus.
Right from the beginning of the Christian era, if not earlier, Hindu ç
religion and culture have spread to all parts of Asia, and some parts ç
of the Middle-East as also Siberia and the Americas. It will be interesting ç
to study this phenomenon to enrich our own knowledge of the same.
